[normal]It cannot be any longer legitimately argued that people in the UK who cannot fund the BBC or do not wan
[normal]t to fund the BBC should any longer be denied access to all live television programme services as a consequence.  The argument deployed against subscription funding of the BBC by willing subscribers was and is that subscription excludes those with the leas
[normal]t money to be able to afford the subscription.  The fact of the matter is that people are already excluding themselves from the BBC and
[normal] 
[normal]all 
[normal]live television programme services
[normal] in the UK
[normal] altogether either through choice or 
[normal]fear 
[normal]because they cannot afford eit
[normal]her the cost of the BBC tv licence nor the 
[normal]fines, 
[normal]costs
[normal] and victim surcharges 
[normal]associated with 
[normal]being prosecuted and convicted for
[normal] so called tv licence evasion.  Exclusion already 
[normal]h
[normal]appens
[normal] under the present 
[normal]broadcast receiving
[normal] licence funding model for and op
[normal]erated by the BBC.  Were the B
[normal]BC tv licence to scrapped, and we
[normal] firmly believe that the BBC tv licence 
[normal]and the Charter obligations cited and deployed as excuses f
[normal]or the continuation of the BBC broadcast receiving
[normal] licence 
[normal]should be scrapped at the earliest 
[normal]opportunity, then people in the UK would still have access to live television programme services for which they would not have to pay a subscription for and not face the 
[normal]fear
[normal] of prosecution and conviction because they were unable 
[normal]to afford to 
[normal]or unwilling 
[normal]to pay 
[normal]into 
[normal]the BBC
[normal] and its
[normal] 
[normal]broadcast receiving
[normal] licence.
